Answers

   Relevance
   [115]Rating [116]Newest [117]Oldest
   [118]Cubbi
   Best Answer:  There is no buffer clearing functions for the input
   streams, but there are functions that consume unprocessed input. You
   can consume input from cin using
        std::cin.ignore(); // consume one character
   or something like
        std::cin.ignore(100, '\n'); // consume characters until end of
   line is consumed or 100 characters are consumed.
   If you want the most robust way to consume all input until (and
   including) the next end of line, it is
        std::cin.ignore( std::numeric_limits< std::streamsize >::max(),
   '\n');
   (don't forget to #include <limits> for numeric_limits)
   Source(s):
   [119]Cubbi · 5 years ago
